An informational meeting for the 2021 trip to Washington D.C. / New York City will be held via Google Meet at 6pm on Wednesday, September 16th.

The trip is a 5-day, expenses paid opportunity to visit two staple cities of American culture. This trip is open to all current 8th grade students.

Please review the invitation attached for the link to the Google Meet and information about the trip itself.

If you have questions, please contact Lyndzie O’Keefe at lokeefe@stockton.k12.mo.us or Cary Chambers at caryjchambers@gmail.com

We hope to see you (virtually) next Wednesday!

Stockton MS First Day of School Reminders:

- Doors open at 7:30 am. Student will report directly to 1st-hour classes (5th-grade students report to homerooms). For students wanting breakfast, MS breakfast will in the MS gym. Students will get their breakfast then go to their classroom. Extra copies of schedules will be available in the hallway by the MS office in the morning.
- Students will be asked to wear a mask during transition times and events when social distancing can not happen.
- Students please bring a water bottle to use throughout the day.
- Students can use a backpack throughout the day to carry their belongings.
- 8th-grade students must have up to date immunizations or signed waiver in order to attend tomorrow.

Stockton MS is so excited about starting back! We are ready to see our students tomorrow. Go Tigers!!

Attention Elementary Families:
The end of day elementary pick up process has been changed for the upcoming school year. Attached is a map of how the process will work. Please note the direction flow of traffic, this will make the car line run more efficient, as well as save you time. Staff will meet you at your car with walkie-talkies to call for your child. We will then bring your child out to the marked spot from the cafeteria. No need to get out of your car. Yellow car tags will be handed out at Open House on Thursday evening. These will need to be prominently displayed as you pick up your children. Official release is 3:25.
Drop off is at the same location. Doors open at 7:30 with the school day beginning at 7:50.

Parents and community -
Since mid March Stockton teachers have been anticipating the return of students to our buildings. The time is almost here. As you can imagine, they have been working tirelessly to prepare their classrooms in a way to protect our kids. I am so proud of the work the teachers and administration have done. Please take the time to share the following thoughts-
Why are teachers important to you and your kids? I know they will appreciate your kind words and the encouragement will help us to start the school year “Stockton Strong”.

post_text:
Stockton R1 is seeking applicants to work in Health Services. Working in conjunction with the RN in charge, you will help to oversee the emotional, mental, physical and social health of students. As an assistant, you may work at any level of education from preschool to high school to provide students with basic health services throughout the school day. You will help manage students who have chronic health conditions and students with disabilities which could include giving them medication as needed and working with parents and teachers to create and enforce care plans. Applicant must either be enrolled in a nursing program working toward a degree in nursing or an LPN. Position will be part-time for the 2020-2021 school year.

Applications can be found at www.stockton.k12.mo.us or picked up at the Superintendents office. Please return applications to the Superintendents office.

post_text:
Dear Parents and Guardians,
Please complete the following survey to help us in developing plans for opening school in the Fall. At this time, we are working on a number of ways to provide education services to students in a safe manner. While we all hope school looks the same as it has in the past, we need to prepare for a number of scenarios. The information provided in this survey will help us formulate those plans.
When completing the survey, please do so with your student(s). We would like to have feedback about our strengths and weaknesses during virtual learning at the end of the school year. There is also a comment section at the bottom of the survey and we encourage you to provide information you feel is important. This information will help us make local decisions along with the guidance provided by the state and the local health department.
Please have the survey completed by Monday, July 6th. Thank you for your time as we prepare for next year.

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSc5kLu3X5LvaFaHfjT7QIaO-evwxEJX72Br3M01BSQ1tjBoTw/viewform

Reminder that USDA food boxes will be distributed at Stockton Schools on Fridays, starting June 5th. These boxes will be provided free of charge for any resident of Cedar County or surrounding areas that is in need of food regardless of income. You do not have to have children to get a box.

Distribution will be drive through and volunteers will load them in your vehicle. You will not have to get out of the car. I believe these boxes will be primarly fresh fruits and vegetables.

Distribution will start at 11:00 am and continue as long as the supply holds out.

Spread the word so that we can get this food distributed to people in our community!

This is in addition to the student meals we are providing for pickup through June 30th. Families can participate in both.

post_text:
USDA food boxes will be distributed at Stockton Schools on Fridays, starting June 5th. These boxes will be provided free of charge for any resident of Cedar County or surrounding areas that is in need of food regardless of income.

Distribution will be drive through and volunteers will load them in your vehicle. You will not have to get out of the car. I believe these boxes will be primarly fresh fruits and vegetables.

Distribution will start at 11:00 am and continue as long as the supply holds out.

Spread the word so that we can get this food distributed to people in our community!

Local churches and service organizations are welcome to organize pickup and delivery for older folks or people who cannot pickup on their own.

post_text:
After careful consideration about student and staff safety, we have decided to not have regular summer school this year. Social distancing will be almost impossible for transportation, in the classrooms, and in the lunchroom. We will offer our 8th grade Algebra 1 course, along with ACT prep, with some modifications to include virtual instruction. Virtual courses offered by Launch will be available to high school students with internet access. A course list will be posted at a later date.

To participate in the ACT prep class, students must have completed Algebra II. To enroll in the ACT prep course, contact Mr. John Woods at jwoods@stockton.k12.mo.us

Dear Families,
We are pleased to announce that our Little Tigers Preschool enrollment will be held on Saturday, June 6th. This will coincide with the kindergarten screening date. Parents please bring an updated shot record, and birth certificate to be copied, as well as a proof of residence. You will fill out enrollment information at this time. Please come and fill out the papers even if you have previously contacted us, and/or are on the waiting list. The preschool program is available for 4 year old students in the school district. If you would like to be added to our waiting list prior to enrollment, or have any questions please contact Erin Hillsman at ehillsman@stockton.k12.mo.us.
Thank you!

post_text: We are excited to announce the hiring of our new boys basketball coach Mike Draper. Coach Draper comes to us from Keytesville, Mo. Coach Draper is very excited to get started and invest in the Stockton community.

post_text:
Class of 2020 seniors and parents:
As Dr. Snow indicated earlier today, we are planning on graduation for May 17th at 2 pm on the football field observing social distancing procedures which are in place. Students will have a limit of 6 guests who can attend.
You will be able to have a walking partner. We will also have speeches from the class president, valedictorian, and salutatorian along with my remarks.
If you are a senior currently failing a required class for graduation, you must be passing in order to participate. Teachers have been working hard to get you the materials and opportunities to be successful. Take advantage of this. Work turned in will receive a grade that can only help you. Get it turned in. Next packet pickup and completed work drop off will be on April 30th at the high school circle drive or sent to you electronically.
I have attached the results of the graduation options survey completed by the seniors.
Continue to be safe and I look forward to seeing you at graduation!

Federal and State Laws require that the Federal and State Constitution be taken and passed by every student and their High School Transcripts indicate this. Juniors were not made Exempt. Federal and State Constitution Test were made available for every student in the April 9th Packet and Electronically in Google Classroom.

Every Junior must take the Missouri Constitution Test.

Constitution Tests must be turned in on or by April 30th along with your Textbook. Thank You.

Attention to anyone with children in the Stockton School District!!!!

Everyone who has children, or takes care of someone else's children during this school wellness closure can receive free meals.

Your children Do Not have to be enrolled in school. These meals are FREE to all children ages 0-18, regardless of income. Please sign up below so we can have an accurate count to prepare for. Meals are available for pickup on Thursdays starting at 9:00 am (see the schedule on the form). You will receive enough food for 7 days of breakfasts and 7 days of lunches per student.

Thursday, April 9th will be our next packet pick-up date. These packets will last you through April 24th. Pick up times will be from 9:00 a.m.-12:00 p.m.

If you cannot make this time, please reach out to someone and see if they can pick up your child’s packet.

High School- Packets will be picked up from the circle drive in front of the high school. Homework information will continue to be sent to Stockton student email accounts, the remind app, and google classroom.

Middle School – Packets will be posted and uploaded on teacher webpages and google classrooms. Paper pick-up will be in the circle drive during the times stated above.

Elementary – Packets will be available for pick-up in the circle drive. Please continue to check DOJO frequently as this is the best way for us to communicate with you.

Drop off boxes will be located in front of each main office.

After this week, we will go to a once per week pickup/delivery option to limit contact. Meals will be available for pickup and delivery as normal on THURSDAY ONLY. Beginning Thursday, April 9th you will receive 7 days of meals.

Tuesday, March 31 – 2 days of meals pickup/delivery

Thursday, April 2 – 5 days of meals pickup/delivery

Thursday, April 9 – 7 days of meals pickup/delivery

Thursday, April 16 – 7 days of meals pickup/delivery

We will continue this schedule as long as we have healthy cafeteria workers and volunteers!

Thank you,

post_text:
Parents and students,

Due to the continued concerns related to Covid-19, and the extension of school being closed through April 24th, Stockton R-1 Schools has made the decision to cancel Prom on April 18th. If conditions improve before graduation time, we will make every effort to have a scaled down version of Prom for students at a later date. However, at this time, there are no guarantees. If the Covid-19 guidelines change where large groups can be together, a reschedule date will be announced.
I have been in contact with The Venue and they have agreed to refund the money that had been collected for the reservation. Those who were planning on bringing underclassmen or outside guests will have the $100 fee reimbursed.
Be safe and know that we are thinking about you everyday.
Go Tigers!

The Stockton R-1 School District can confirm that we have had a positive case of the COVID-19 virus. We will not release the name of the individual, but anyone that has had exposure to the individual has been individually notified by school administrators. Cedar County Health Department officials will also be contacting those who have had exposure.

Please do not panic. If you received a phone call, please observe quarantine procedures and follow health department advice.

If you did not receive a phone call, please continue to follow isolation protocol and do not contribute to misinformation going around.

Missouri FFA Association
March 14 at 7:36 PM ·

Ag Ed/FFA Family,
In light of the current health issues and concerns resulting from the coronavirus (COVID-19), the State FFA Convention scheduled for April 23 and 24 is being postponed. Ag Ed staff members are working on a contingency plan for the State Convention program, State Leadership Development and State Career Development Events. My recommendation is that you reconsider holding all area and district FFA events involving significant numbers of students. While a variety of factors go into making a decision like this, be assured that the health and safety of our students and stakeholders is always our primary concern.

As an association we know there will be questions. We are evlauating all options as we move through the next few days and weeks. Continue to check with your advisor and watch social media.

post_text:
Our custodians have been in flu cleaning mode for quite some time now.

We have foggers that can spray disinfectant into rooms and hallways. Our disinfectants are rated for COVID-19. We are wiping surfaces, such as desktops, tables, water fountains, and doorknobs to name a few, daily. Custodians are also wiping and spraying down bus seats to prevent the spread of germs.

Our teachers and nurse are emphasizing proper and frequent hand washing to all students.

If your student is sick, keep them at home.

We are hoping to prevent the spread of unnecessary germs!

post_text: Scholar Bowl took a team of five to the Fair Grove Invitational on Saturday, March 7th. The Invitational was comprised of 28 teams from the Greater Southwest of Missouri. They went 6-3 in pool play coming in third in their pool, and went into the consolation bracket against Strafford in a close game that came down to the wire in the 20th Round on the tossup question. They lost, but went on to win the next two matches against Strafford B and won a rematch against Richland to finish 8-4 on the day and a 7th place in the tournament. Michael Brown received a medal for tying 7th amongst point leaders averaging 52.4 points a game in pool play and his second medal so far by placing 5th in points per game at districts at Forsyth in early February. Next tournament is at Joplin Christian Academy, March 28th.

post_text:
The Stockton Community Teachers Association will host the Board of Education Candidate Forum on March 19, 2020. The event will begin at 6:30 p.m. in the High School Library. During the event, candidates will be given an opportunity to respond to the following questions:
As a potential board member, what is your highest priority?
The governor supports increasing teacher salaries, but does not plan to increase funding for this initiative. Where do you stand on this issue, and how would you plan to keep teacher salaries competitive?

Stockton School District has seen a steady decline in enrollment during the past few years. Moving forward, what do you see as the fiscal priorities as the enrollment and budget decreases?
How do you feel about homeschool students participating in Stockton school extracurricular activities?
What could be done to increase parent involvement?
The public is encouraged to attend. Refreshments will be provided.

post_text: Kindergarten Screening for 2020-2021 is April 20th from 10 am- 7 pm. It will be held in the elementary cafeteria. This is the only day we will be doing screening. If you have a child who will be 5 years of age by August 1st, they are eligible for Kindergarten. Please contact Teresa Farwell at 417-276-5143 ext 380 to schedule a screening time. Your child cannot be screened without an appointment. You must have shot records and birth certificate. The first day of school is August 25th. Incoming Kindergarten, 8th grade and Seniors will be required to have their booster shots and proof of those shots. Please reach out to your local health department at 417-276-6416 or your primary care doctor for booster shots. According to state regulations your child cannot attend school without required vaccinations. Please help spread the word.

post_text: The Stockton R-1 School District is accepting sealed bids for a 1997 International bus. The bus can be viewed at the bus barn during school hours or by contacting Matt York at 417-276-5143 ext 224. Sealed bids should be delivered to the superintendent’s office by Wednesday, March 18th at 3:00 pm. Minimum bid is $800. Winning bidder will be notified on Thursday, March 19th and will have 7 days to make payment and remove the bus.

shared_text:
Stockton Community Foundation
February 20 at 8:00 AM ·

FEATURED SCHOLARSHIP FUND:

Larry L. Jones Memorial Scholarship

This scholarship was started in 2012 by Larry Jones family after he passed away from an accident. His family remarks how Larry was an "all around good person, good student & good athlete", a lifelong learner & advocate of higher education & continuing education beyond graduation. He loved the Stockton community & Joplin community from which he graduated from MSSU. The schloarship awards $1,000.00 & can be renewable for 4 yrs.

Student must be going to MSSU in Joplin & have maintained a 3.0 GPA as a Senior. Application can be picked up at high school counselor office or from the "Scholarship Wall". Info required from the student includes work history, school activities, community activities, other scholarships applied for, letters of recommendation & an essay as to what your goals are for the future.

📅This one is due MARCH 4, 2020.

🎓Recipient for 2019 was Liana Bothman.

post_text: Again, there are no confirmed cases. We are merely providing precautionary information to be proactive.
shared_text:
Cedar County Memorial Hospital
January 29 at 1:48 PM ·

A Message from the Cedar County Health Department

Attn: All Parents & Residents in the Stockton Community

There are NO CONFIRMED CASES OF MUMPS in the STOCKTON school or community. A group of students travelled outside of the community over the weekend of January 25 and were exposed to a a CONFIRMED CASE in another community.

The incubabtion period of mumps is 16 to 18 days. The initial symptoms are flu-like, including body aches, lack of appetite, headache, and low-grade fever. Mumps is generally characterized by swelling of one or more salivary glands, usually the parotid glands. If you feel your child has symptoms, please seek a medical evaluation from your health care provider.

For further updates, watch the Stockton R-1 School District's Facebook page.

For more information, please contact the Cedar County Health Department at 417/276-6416 or 417/876-5477.

Thank you.

Jenean Ehlers, RN, Community Services Manager
Cedar County Health Department
